Snowshoe Hares in Bonanza Creek: Exploratory Report

Craig Kopulsky

11/17/2020

Hare sizes and weights in the Bonanza Creek: exploratory report

1. Introduction

Snowshoe hares are important to monitor, as they are a keystone species in northern boreal forests, and their populations experience fluctuations over 8-11 year periods (Kielland et al.2017). In this report, we focus on juvenile snowshoe hares observed at Bonanza Creek in Alaska from 1999-2012, and investigate the weight distribution of juvenile snowshoe hares by sex and the site at Bonanza they were trapped at, as well as the relationship between weight and hind foot length for juvenile snowshoe hares in general.

These explanations from the metadata file for the study give detail on the three sites that will be referred to throughout this report:

Riperian: Bonanza Riparian is a flood zone along the Tanana River and Bonanza Mature is a mature black spruce forest approximately 1 km inland from the river and 2 km from the riparian plot. Bonanza Riparian consisted of willow (Salix spp.), paper birch (Betula papyrifera), alder (Alnus spp.), white spruce (Picea glauca), fireweed (Epilobium augustifolium) and several grasses. Site used for live-trapping snowshoe hares to monitor abundance and survival. (Kielland et al.2017)

Mature: Bonanza Mature consisted of stands of mature white spruce, paper birch, and alder, as well as black spruce (Picea mariana), Labrador tea (Ledum groenlandicum), willows, and prickly rose (Rosa acicularis). (Kielland et al.2017)

Lowland: Site used for live-trapping snowshoe hares to monitor abundance and survival. Located in a mature lowland black spruce stand. (Kielland et al.2017)

2. Data analysis

Snowshoe hares were collected and measured by Dr.Knut Kielland and colleagues at the Institute of Arctic Biology, who made this data available for use. The data set used in this report contains data for sex, age, weight, and size for snowshoe hares in Bonanza Creek Experimental Forest for the duration of the study. This data set contains 3197 total observations for snowshoe hares observered through capture-recapture studies at the Bonanza Creek Experimental Forest location. After exploratory data visualization is carried out in this analysis, weights between male and female juvenile hares are compared by two-sample t-tests using a significance level (\(\alpha\)) of 0.05. Differences between the mean weights of the male and female juvenile hares are described by Cohens d effect size. The relationship between hind leg length and weight is explored by simple linear regression. All analyses are in R version 4.0.2 using RStudio version 1.3.1073.

3. Exploratory findings

Annual juvenile hare trap counts

Figure 1. Total juvenile hares recorded in Bonanza Creek for each year of the study. Data: Kielland et al.(2017)

The average number of juvenile hares trapped yearly in Bonanza Creek from 1999 - 2012 is 27 hares and the median number trapped yearly is 15.5 hares. The maximum number of juvenile hares trapped during this time period was 126 in 1999 and the minimum number trapped was 0 in both 2002 and 2009. After the initial peak in 1999, annual juvenile hares trapped drops off significantly. This is likely due in some part to declining population and subsequent population fluctuations of hares over this time period. Effort in data collection is likely a factor as well; future analysis of this ongoing data collection effort can account for the effort put into trapping and recording hares with respect to number of days and number of traps in the study each year by weighting the data with respect to effort. Many hares throughout the study were not recorded with an age, including none in 1998 (the metadata for the study also indicates that the study began in 1999, despite data included for 1998). For this reason, 1998 is not included in this juvenile hares trapped by year analysis, but the numbers reported here could be under representing the true total juvenile hares trapped if some of those that were not classified on age were indeed juveniles.

Juvenile hare weights (g) were compared across sex and site where they were trapped. Both the males trapped at the Lowland site (1073.08 222.64 g, n = 13; mean 1 standard deviation) and females trapped at the Lowland site (1022.06 292.96 g, n = 34) were heavier than their geneder counterparts at the other sites: males trapped at the Mature site (950.12 314.69 g, n = 40), males trapped at the Riperian site(929.27 349.17 g, n = 110), females trapped at the Mature site(808.19 361.12 g, n = 36), and females trapped at the Riperian site(824.15 255.04 g, n = 127). As expected, the males observed at each site were heavier than females observed at the same site, but the difference in means between male and female juvenile hares at the Lowland site is only 51.02g, a 4.87% difference. less than the difference betweeen males and females at the other sites. Most sex by site groups appear to be relatively normally distributed, as the means and medians are relatively close together. The Mature site female group exhibits a somewhat leftward skew on its weight distribution, as the mean is higher than the median, and the Lowland and Riperian male groups exhibit some skew to the right.

Juvenile weight comparison (male and female snowshoe hares)

Table 2. Descriptive statistics (mean, median, standard deviation, and sample size) for juvenile hares observed in Bonanza Creek, by sex. Data: Kielland et al.(2017)
Sex Mean Weight (g) Median Weight (g) Standard Deviation (g) Sample Size
Female 855.3909 825 292.2526 197
Male 945.8589 990 333.2151 163

Juvenile male hares are heavier than juvenile female hares on average (945.86 \(\pm\) 333.22 and 855.39 \(\pm\) 292.25 g, respectively; mean \(\pm\) 1 standard deviation). The difference in the means is 90.47, a 10.05% difference. The difference in means is significant (Welchs two-sample t-test: t(325.02) = 2.71, p < 0.001), and the effect size is moderate (Cohens d = 0.29).

Relationship between juvenile weight and hind foot length

Figure 3. Relationship between hind foot length (mm) and weight (g) by for all juvenile hares trapped in Bonanza Creek and recorded for the study. Linear model summary: \(\beta\)1 = 9.52 g mm-1, p < 0.001, R2 = 0.3, Pearsons r = 0.55). Data: Kielland et al.(2017)

The linear regression model applied to these observations for weight and hind foot length indicates that as hare hind foot length increases by 1 mm, weight tends to increase by 9.52 g. The R2 value of 0.3 indicates these two variables do not have a strong linear relationship, but the Pearsons r of 0.55 indicates a medium positive correlation. As p < 0.001 for this model, we can be confident that there is some correlation between these variables. A normal Q-Q plot of the residuals shows that the residuals are somewhat normal, yet slightly skewed to the right. A concern with this linear model is that there is a significant amount of data that falls below the linear regression line. Thus, the model is heteroscedastic, as the residuals increase as hind foot length increases. In addition, it is possible that an exponential or logarithmic function may fit the data better, so this should be investigated as well.

Summary

Exploratory data analysis of juvenile hares recorded in Bonanza Creek reveals the following:

  • There is high variation in the number of juvenile hares sampled by year, with the sample declining sharply after 1999
  • Weights for males and females at each site appear to exhibit some level of normality
  • Juvenile male hares are heavier than juvenile female hares on average
  • There is a medium positive correlation between hind foot length (mm) and weight (g) for juvenile hares recorded at Bonanza Creek

Next steps:

  • Past trapping efforts throughout the study should be thoroughly investigated in order to determine if the drops in observations of juvenile hares from 1999 on, and subsequent annual fluctuations, can be best accounted for by varying effort levels in data collection or if changing population levels, movement patterns, or other factors for hares in Bonanza Creek should be weighted more heavily.
  • Records with high residuals for the linear regression model in Figure 3, particularly those below the best fit line of regression, should be investigated to see if there is anything unique about these cases relative to the rest of the juvenile hare sample in the model. If there is reason to believe this sample is very different than the rest of the juvenile snowshoe hare sample, this sample could be removed for some exploratory modeling or this information could be considered in explaining the correlations derived in future analysis.
  • Alternative models should be explored to investigate whether there is a better fit for the data than the linear regression model used here.
